    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I've been doing a lot of HIIT lately and I keep hearing people talk about \"lactic acid buildup\" and that burning sensation in the muscles. Can you explain the actual biochemistry of how lactic acid is produced during high intensity work and how the body clears it out afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid buildup during HIIT, also known as lactic acidosis, occurs when your muscles switch from aerobic to anaerobic metabolism, producing energy through the breakdown of glucose without sufficient oxygen. This process is initiated by the enzyme lactate dehydrogenase (LDH), which converts pyruvate, a byproduct of glycolysis, into lactic acid. As your body produces more lactic acid, it can lead to a burning sensation in your muscles, which is often referred to as 'lactic acid cramp.' The body typically clears out lactic acid through the liver and kidneys, which convert it back into glucose and excrete it in the urine. This process can take several hours to complete.",
      "source": "target",
